To terminate a C program, you can use the `exit()` function from the `stdlib.h` library. This function takes an integer argument, which represents the status code to be returned to the system. Here's an example of how to use it:

```c
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
    // Your program code here

    exit(status); // Replace 'status' with the desired exit status

    return 0; // This line is optional and will be ignored if exit() is called
}
```

By calling `exit(status)`, the program will terminate immediately and the specified status code will be returned to the system. The `return 0;` statement is optional and is used to indicate a successful program termination. However, if `exit()` is called, the `return` statement will be ignored.

Alternatively, you can also use the `return` statement at the end of the `main()` function to terminate the program. This method is simpler and more commonly used. Here's an example:

```c
int main() {
    // Your program code here

    return status; // Replace 'status' with the desired exit status
}
```

By using `return status;`, the program will terminate and the specified status code will be returned to the system.
